The People's Republic of China, the French Republic, the Russian Federation, the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland, and the United States of America have declared their commitment to avoiding war between nuclear-weapon states and reducing strategic risks. They believe that a nuclear war cannot be won and should never be fought. They affirm that nuclear weapons should only serve defensive purposes, deter aggression, and prevent war. They strongly oppose the further spread of nuclear weapons. They emphasize the importance of adhering to non-proliferation, disarmament, and arms control agreements. They are committed to pursuing negotiations for nuclear disarmament and a world without nuclear weapons. They will maintain and strengthen national measures to prevent unauthorized use of nuclear weapons. They confirm that none of their nuclear weapons are targeted at each other or any other state. They aim to work with all states to create a security environment conducive to disarmament. They will seek diplomatic approaches to avoid military confrontations, enhance stability and predictability, foster mutual understanding and confidence, and prevent an arms race. They are determined to engage in constructive dialogue while respecting each other's security interests and concerns.